Plans are made with the community emergency response groups as well as onsite emergency response teams to ensure procedures are in place in case an emergency situation occurs.

In addition, General ChemicalA?s Richmond Works has taken additional chemical-specific prevention steps designed to perform the following: 

A?    Quickly detect a release of oleum; 
A?    Contain or control a release of oleum;
A?    And/or, reduce the consequences of a release of oleum.

The following types of safety features are used in various processes:

Release Detection

A?    Process temperature and pressure controls;
A?    Operator surveillance of all process areas;
A?    Oleum process equipment level alarms; and 

Release Containment and Control

A?    Pressure relief devices on storage units and process vessels;
A?    Secondary containment for oleum process vessel;
A?    Oleum produced in small quantities to reduce the impact of a potential release; and
A?    Automatic and manual shutdown systems on process equipment.

Release Mitigation

A?    Emergency shutdown procedures;
A?    Trained emergency response personnel;
A?    Notification procedures for plant personnel and local officials;
A?    Personal protective equipment for emergency response personnel; and
A?    Emergency Response plans prepared with local emergency response officials.

